                type="document" xml:id="d5">
                <head>5. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 68, “United States Objectives and Programs
                    for National Security,” April 14, 1950, is printed in <ref
                        target="frus1950v01#pg_234">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1950, volume I, pages
                        234</ref>–<ref target="frus1950v01#pg_292">292</ref>. The National Security
                    Council adopted <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 68 on April 25, but
                    President <persName corresp="#p_THS1">Truman</persName> did not approve it until
                    September 30. The paper envisioned, among other things, a dramatic increase in
                    defense spending, particularly in the form of covert action operations directed
                    against the Soviet Union and its satellites. For subsequent papers in the <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 68 series and related documentation, see the
                    compilation on national security policy, <ref target="frus1951v01">ibid., 1951,
                        volume I</ref>.</p>
            </div>
